\n<td style=\"width: 211px; height: 24px;\">From 26/12/2018 to\r\n28/12/2018 by 5.00 p.m</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 24px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 59px; height: 24px;\">4</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 363px; height: 24px;\">Display of vacancy on Notice Board (if any)</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 211px; height: 24px;\">28/12/2018 by 6.30 p.m</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 24px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 59px; height: 24px;\">5</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 363px; height: 24px;\">Waitlisted candidate from the Merit List to\r\nreport to respective college against vacancy\r\n(if any)</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 211px; height: 24px;\">From 29/12/2018, 11.00 a.m.\r\nto 30/12/2018, 5.00 p.m</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<strong>Note: The candidate should read rules of eligibility and other details before submitting the application form.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>(A) Eligibility Criteria for B. Sc. Optometry for Academic Year 2018-19:-</strong>\r\n\r\n1. The Candidate has passed Higher Secondary (10+2) with 50% marks with Physic, Chemistry and Biology group for open category and 40o/o marks for reserve category. The candidates must have passed English at HSC (10+2 Course). If the sufficient number of eligible candidate are not available then eligibility of HSC (PCB) criteria may be relaxed subject to approval MUHS Nashik.\r\n\r\n2. The candidate has attained the age 17 Years as on 31 December of the year of the admission.\r\n\r\n3. The candidate has to furnish a certificate of Physical Fitness form registered Medical Practitioner at the time of admission.\r\n\r\n4′ The preference will be given to candidates who have passed 10th &amp;amp; 12th from Maharashtra and also domicile of Maharashtra. if such a candidate is not available the non-domicile of Maharashtra candidates will be admitted as mentioned in the selection process.\r\n\r\n5′ 15% of seat Intake capacity will be filled by the institution as institutional quota seats.\r\n\r\n6′ 25% of seats of Intake capacity will be reserved for constitutional reserve candidates.\r\n\r\n7. The Hostel accommodation will not be provided to admitted students.\r\n\r\n8. Rules of Tiebreaker HSC (10+2 course) candidates –&amp;nbsp;the candidate with Higher PCB marks will be preferred.\r\n\r\na. The candidate with higher marks in Biology at HSC will be preferred.\r\n\r\nb. If Tie persists then the candidate with higher marks in Chemistry at HSC will be preferred.\r\n\r\nc. If Tie persists the older candidate will be preferred.\r\n\r\n<strong>(B) Fee Structure:-</strong>\r\n<table style=\"height: 49px;\" width=\"522\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 25px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 123px; height: 25px;\">First Year</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 123px; height: 25px;\">Second Year</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 124px; height: 25px;\">Third Year</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 124px; height: 25px;\">Fourth Year</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 24px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 123px; height: 24px;\">Rs. 80,000/</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 123px; height: 24px;\">Rs. 80,000/</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 124px; height: 24px;\">Rs. 80,000/</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 124px; height: 24px;\">(Internship)\r\nNo Tuition Fees</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<strong>(C) Duration of the Courses:-</strong>\r\n\r\nThe B. Sc. Optometry Degree program is of years duration (3+l)including I years compulsory internship.\r\n\r\n<strong>(D) The medium of Instruction:-</strong>\r\n\r\nEnglish shall be medium of the instruction for all the subjects of study and for examinations of the course.\r\n\r\n<strong>(E) Selection Process:-</strong>\r\n\r\nThe selection will be done in order of following Types of the students in descending order from a to d.\r\n\r\na. The candidate who have passed 10th and 12th from Maharashtra as well as Domicile Maharashtra.\r\n\r\nb.The candidate who have passed 10th and 12th from outside Maharashtra but Domicile of Maharashtra.\r\n\r\nc.The candidate who have passed lOth and 12th from Maharashtra but NoT Domicile of Maharashtra.\r\n\r\nd. The candidate who have passed 10th and l2th from outside Maharashtra but NOT Domicile of Maharashtra.\r\n\r\nFor more details click on the link mention below:\r\n\r\n<span class=\"webkit-html-attribute-value\">https://www.dmer.org/new/B.Sc%20Optometry%20AY%202018-19.pdf</span>','DMER Maharashtra: Admission to Degree Courses in BSc Optometry for Academic Year 2018-19','','inherit','closed','closed','','856-revision-v1','','','2019-07-18 12:36:11','2019-07-18 12:36:11','',856,'http://test.hvd.com/2019/07/18/856-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(861,1,'2019-07-18 12:43:30','2019-07-18 12:43:30','<strong>Medical device manufacturer ZEISS has joined forces with the Christoffel Mission for the Blind (CBM) to establish a new cataract surgery training centre in India.</strong>\r\n\r\nDoctors will be specifically trained in phacoemulsification at the H.V. Desai Eye Hospital, Pune, in a project that is expected to help thousands of Indians regain their sight.\r\n\r\nThe renowned eye care clinic serves a region of more than 37 million people and conducts field visits within a 350km radius. In the past year alone, more than 580,000 patients sought help from the hospital, with 34,000 of those undergoing cataract surgery.\r\n\r\nZeiss and CBM have also penned an agreement with the Poona Blind Men Association, which operates the hospital and will cover the cost of cataract surgery for patients who cannot afford it.\r\n\r\n\"In India, one of the world\'s most populous countries, there is a real need for ophthalmologists with the right training. With this new centre, we\'re doing our part to enable top-quality ophthalmic care. In the future, poorer people in remote regions will also benefit from this.\" CBM CEO Dr Rainer Brockhaus said.\r\n\r\nCarl Zeiss Meditec chairman Dr Ludwin Monz said the new phacoemulsification training centre was the result of a longstanding collaboration between CBM and Zeiss. The two entities previously combined to open a specialist training centre in Paraguay last year.\r\n\r\n“Thanks to this collaboration, we\'re helping to establish modern ophthalmic techniques in countries like India, thereby improving eye care treatment for patients,\" he said.\r\n\r\nPhacoemulsification has been a standard procedure in countries such as Germany for several decades. However, it has been much slower in reaching many developing countries.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Zeiss opens phaco training centre in India','','publish','closed','closed','','zeiss-opens-phaco-training-centre-in-india','','','2019-07-18 14:03:37','2019-07-18 14:03:37','',0,'http://test.hvd.com/?post_type=news&#038;p=861',0,'news','',0),(862,1,'2019-07-18 12:43:30','2019-07-18 12:43:30','<strong>Medical device manufacturer ZEISS has joined forces with the Christoffel Mission for the Blind (CBM) to establish a new cataract surgery training centre in India.</strong>\r\n\r\nDoctors will be specifically trained in phacoemulsification at the H.V. Desai Eye Hospital, Pune, in a project that is expected to help thousands of Indians regain their sight.\r\n\r\nThe renowned eye care clinic serves a region of more than 37 million people and conducts field visits within a 350km radius. In the past year alone, more than 580,000 patients sought help from the hospital, with 34,000 of those undergoing cataract surgery.\r\n\r\nZeiss and CBM have also penned an agreement with the Poona Blind Men Association, which operates the hospital and will cover the cost of cataract surgery for patients who cannot afford it.\r\n\r\n\"In India, one of the world\'s most populous countries, there is a real need for ophthalmologists with the right training. With this new centre, we\'re doing our part to enable top-quality ophthalmic care. In the future, poorer people in remote regions will also benefit from this.\" CBM CEO Dr Rainer Brockhaus said.\r\n\r\nCarl Zeiss Meditec chairman Dr Ludwin Monz said the new phacoemulsification training centre was the result of a longstanding collaboration between CBM and Zeiss. The two entities previously combined to open a specialist training centre in Paraguay last year.\r\n\r\n“Thanks to this collaboration, we\'re helping to establish modern ophthalmic techniques in countries like India, thereby improving eye care treatment for patients,\" he said.\r\n\r\nPhacoemulsification has been a standard procedure in countries such as Germany for several decades. However, it has been much slower in reaching many developing countries.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Zeiss opens phaco training centre in India','','inherit','closed','closed','','861-revision-v1','','','2019-07-18 12:43:30','2019-07-18 12:43:30','',861,'http://test.hvd.com/2019/07/18/861-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(863,1,'2019-07-18 13:24:23','2019-07-18 13:24:23','','hero-traning','','inherit','open','closed','','hero-traning','','','2019-07-18 13:24:23','2019-07-18 13:24:23','',0,'http://test.hvd.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/hero-traning.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(864,1,'2019-07-18 13:27:33','2019-07-18 13:27:33','','5a99e16c9afc1.image','','inherit','open','closed','','5a99e16c9afc1-image','','','2019-07-18 13:27:33','2019-07-18 13:27:33','',0,'http://test.hvd.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/5a99e16c9afc1.image_.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(865,1,'2019-07-18 13:35:56','2019-07-18 13:35:56','<p class=\"m-story-header__intro\"><strong>The Iksha Foundation, a Bengaluru-based NGO supporting children with eye cancer, has stepped up programmes to spread awareness about retinoblastoma and ensure that the disease is detected in potential victims in its early stages.</strong></p>\r\nThe Iksha Foundation, a Bengaluru-based NGO supporting children with eye cancer, has stepped up programmes to spread awareness about retinoblastoma and ensure that the disease is detected in potential victims in its early stages. One week in May, starting from the second Sunday of the month — May 13 to May 19 this year — is observed as World Retinoblastoma Week, to raise awareness about retinoblastoma (RB), which is a life-threatening eye cancer affecting newborn and very young children up to 5 years of age.\r\n\r\nIt can occur either in one eye or both. According to Iksha Foundation, reported incidences of RB are increasing. Doctors suggest systemising eye screenings for toddlers will go a long way in preventing childhood blindness.\r\n\r\nAccording to Dr Sonal S Chaugule, consultant, ophthalmic plastic surgery, orbit and ocular oncology, H V Desai Eye Hospital, Pune, “Awareness about retinoblastoma is low and early detection is crucial to give the best chance of saving the child’s life, eye and vision. Early detection and proper treatment will ensure 95 per cent of the children diagnosed with RB are saved from death, 90 per cent have their eye intact and 85 per cent have their vision protected.”\r\n\r\n“Unfortunately, in India, a child is taken to an eye specialist only when there is any notable problem, which makes treatment of RB at a later stage much harder,” she said. Against this background, she suggests that systemised screening of eye for any abnormality in infants/toddlers should be made mandatory and sensitising doctors and healthcare authorities at different levels assumes great importance.\r\n\r\nAccording to Thanmaya Bekkalale, founder and trustee, Iksha Foundation, “We only know the reported cases of RB, there are numerous cases that go unreported. The need of the hour is to spread individual and societal awareness about RB and promote early detection as it is documented that every day, four children are born with eye cancer in India, and one of them is facing death as a result of diagnosis at advanced stage or not diagnosed at all.”','Awareness programmes about Retinoblastoma','','inherit','closed','closed','','524-revision-v1','','','2019-07-18 13:35:56','2019-07-18 13:35:56','',524,'http://test.hvd.com/2019/07/18/524-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(866,1,'2019-07-18 13:36:30','2019-07-